[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Step 1: Generate Synthetic Member Data
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m *The pseudocode calls this `assemble_member_features(member_id, as_of_date)`. In a real system, you'd pull from claims, eligibility, call center, portal, and grievance databases. Here we generate synthetic data that mimics the statistical properties of a real health plan population.*
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def generate_synthetic_members(n_members: int = 5000, churn_rate: float = 0.10) -> pd.DataFrame:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Generate synthetic member data with realistic feature distributions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Real health plan data comes from 6+ source systems. This function creates
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     a single DataFrame that simulates what you'd get after the Glue feature
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     assembly job runs. The distributions are loosely based on published
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     literature on health plan disenrollment patterns.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Args:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         n_members: Number of synthetic members to generate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         churn_rate: Fraction of members who will be labeled as churned.
