[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def prepare_and_upload_training_data(df: pd.DataFrame) -> tuple[str, str]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Split data into train/validation sets and upload to S3.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     SageMaker's built-in XGBoost algorithm expects CSV files with no header,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     where the first column is the label (target variable) and the remaining
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     columns are features in the exact order specified by FEATURE_COLUMNS.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     In production, you'd use time-based splitting: train on data from earlier
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     periods, validate on the most recent period. This prevents data leakage
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     and simulates how the model will actually be used (predicting the future
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     from the past). For this synthetic example, we use stratified random split.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Args:
